## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException + ResetAbort** | catch block swallows abort | `OperationCanceledException` catch |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly terminate a managed thread. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone (`SYSLIB0006`). You must switch to **cooperative cancellation**.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),
            timeout);
    }

    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception aggregates to match original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs After

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — work has no way to know it was cancelled
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — non-cooperative overload still works
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — cooperative overload (preferred)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token => ExpensiveCalculation(token),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

---

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation is not instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token won't interrupt a blocking `Thread.Sleep` or CPU-bound loop. The work must **check the token** at regular intervals. |
| **Fire-and-forget work** | When the non-cooperative overload times out, `Task.Run` keeps executing in the background — it's not killed. The old code truly stopped the thread. If this matters, move uncooperative work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill`. |
| **Dispose the CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` with a timer leaks if not disposed. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only catch *your* timeout, not an unrelated upstream cancellation. |

### Making Existing Work Cooperative

If `ExpensiveCalculation` has a loop, add checkpoints:

```csharp
// Before — no way to stop mid-execution
int ExpensiveCalculation()
{
    var sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10_000_000; i++)
        sum += Compute(i);
    return sum;
}

// After — stops promptly when token fires
int ExpensiveCalculation(CancellationToken token)
{
    var sum = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 10_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        sum += Compute(i);
    }
    return sum;
}
```

The key insight: **`Thread.Abort` was preemptive** (runtime injected an exception anywhere). **`CancellationToken` is cooperative** (your code must opt in at checkpoints). The non-cooperative overload preserves the old API surface, but only the cooperative overload actually stops work promptly.
